# Kotlin Coding Style

## Use Data Classes for Value Objects

Use `data class` for message types, DTOs, and any type whose primary purpose is holding data. This ensures correct `equals`, `hashCode`, and `copy` behaviour automatically.

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD
data class StrokeMessage(val id: String, val points: List<Point>, val timestamp: Long)
```

## JSON Serialization: Use Gson

Use Gson for all JSON serialization and deserialization. Do not introduce `kotlinx.serialization` or Moshi unless the project already uses them.

Create a new `Gson()` instance per call site. Do not share a singleton instance across the codebase — Gson instances are not designed for shared mutable use.

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD
val json = Gson().toJson(message)
val parsed = Gson().fromJson(json, StrokeMessage::class.java)
```

## Logging: Use android.util.Log

Use `android.util.Log` for all logging. Do not introduce Timber or other logging libraries unless the project already uses them.

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD
Log.d(TAG, "Connection established")
Log.e(TAG, "Failed to parse message", exception)
```

Define a `TAG` constant at the top of each class:

```kotlin
companion object {
    private const val TAG = "MyClassName"
}
```
